
[1]pine

   PINE, n. [L. pinus.] A tree of the genus Pinus, of many species, some
   of which furnish timber of the most valuable kind. The species which
   usually bear this name in the United States, are the white pine, Pinus
   strobus,the prince of our forests; the yellow pine, Pinus resinosa; and
   the pitch pine, Pinus rigida. The other species of this genus are
   called by other names, a fir,hemlock, larch, spruce, &c.

   PINE, v.i.

   1. To languish; to lose flesh or wear away under any distress of
   anxiety of mind; to grow lean; followed sometimes by away.

   Ye shall not mourn nor weep, but ye shall pine away for your
   iniquities. Ezek.24.

   2. To languish with desire; to waste away with longing for something;
   usually followed by for.

   Unknowing that she pin'd for your return.

                PINE, v.t. To wear out; to make to languish.

   Where shivering cold and sickness pines the clime.

   Beroe pined with pain.

   1. To grieve for; to bemoan in silence.

   Abashed the devil stood--

   Virtue in her own shape how lovely, saw,

   And pined his loss.

   [In the transitive sense, this verb is now seldom used, and this use is
                       improper, except by ellipsis.]

                     PINE, n. Woe; want; penury; misery.

   [This is obsolete. See Pain.]
